  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Recovery response to flood affected populations in Bamyan province</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In 2016, recurrent small and medium scale natural hazards have struck the central region of Afghanistan. 
Floods and heavy rains have been especially frequent in Bamyan Province in April and May 2016, affecting 1,895 families (ANDMA). Populations were affected though crop losses, destruction of irrigation infrastructures, losses of livestock, shelter destruction and NFIs losses.
According to IOM, 496 households totally or partially lost their housing situation.
Emergency assistance has been provided to those identified families, but IOM could only provide assistance to meet most urgent needs (support to NFIs and Emergency shelter). Some families also received an emergency food distribution for 1 or 2 months from WFP.
      
However, that assistance could not provide affected families with the means to recover their housing situation. For families relying on agricultural activities, the losses of their income sources affected their livelihoods and resilience, preventing any rehabilitation of their damaged homes.
In addition the harsh coming winter in Bamyan Province brings another threat on those affected households.
This is especially true for most vulnerable families who completely lost their house: small land owners, female headed households, big families, families with PSN&#x2026; Those families often have no sustainable coping mechanisms.
400 most vulnerable affected families being in a precarious housing situation (destroyed or damaged house) will receive a specific support to cover their needs for winter. This winterization assistance (heating materials, blankets&#x2026;) will ensure their protection for the 3 months of winter and prevent them from adopting negative coping strategies.
Among those beneficiaries, the project will identify and support 40 households with specific vulnerability criteria and no mid-term capacity to recover their housing situation. Those families will benefit from a shelter assistance to sustainably rehabilitate their damaged or destroyed houses.

The project will then contribute to cover shelter and NFI gaps in the humanitarian assistance in Saighan, Khamard, Shibar, Yakawalang, Penjab, Waraz and Bamyan central districts of Bamyan Province. It will provide recovery and immediate assistance to address residual needs of the most vulnerable disaster affected, in rural areas of Bamyan Province.</narrative>
  </description>
